{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512824"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:01:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:01:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11964"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11964"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.17,0.66,0.03,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4556"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107328"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4556"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11964"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89792"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"387"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1393"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"4046"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9272"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6819"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26947"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33222"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36993"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36996"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41936"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43880"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107328"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 41-year-old man presents with a one month history of anorexia and nausea. There has been no vomiting, abdominal pain, altered bowel habits or weight loss, but he has noticed that his skin has become yellow. His medical history includes hypercholesterolaemia for which he takes atorvastatin daily. He does not take any over-the-counter medications. He says he drinks 2-3 beers daily and this increases to 5-6 on the weekend. He has smoked one pack of cigarettes daily for the last 20 years. He has never used injecting drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination his blood pressure is 130/81mmHg, pulse 74/min, respiratory rate is 15/min and temperature 37\u00b0C. His BMI is 21 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. His skin and sclera are icteric and his abdomen has a mildly enlarged liver with tender liver edge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis complete blood examination shows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHb 124 g/L (130-190)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCV 105 fL(80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC 14 x 10^9/L (4-10)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 110 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA biochemistry metabolic panel is also performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following LFT patterns would be expected?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alanine aminotransferase (ALT): 156, Aspartate aminotransferase (AST): 74","Alanine aminotransferase (ALT): 1500, Aspartate aminotransferase (AST): 1089","Alanine aminotransferase (ALT): 120, Aspartate aminotransferase (AST): 256","Alanine aminotransferase (ALT): 83, Aspartate aminotransferase (AST): 72","Alanine aminotransferase (ALT): 2521, Aspartate aminotransferase (AST): 2222"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u2019s history of chronic alcohol intake, jaundice, tender hepatomegaly, anorexia, and nausea indicates that he has \u003Cstrong\u003Ealcoholic hepatitis. \u003C/strong\u003EWhilst 2-3 beers a day may not seem much, it must always be remembered that most patients are reluctant to divulge their drinking and smoking habits to their doctor and will usually underestimate the quantities. His complete blood examination shows a macrocytic anaemia consistent with alcohol as well as thrombocytopenia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs liver injury develops, regardless of the specific cause, the synthetic functions of the liver are affected. There is a decrease in the synthesis of albumin and coagulation factors (leading to a high INR) and a decrease in the metabolism/excretion of toxins (leading to a high bilirubin). Reduced synthesis of TPO and portal hypertension can lead to thrombocytopenia. The liver function tests (LFTs - AST, ALT, GGT) can indicate the likely underlying cause of liver damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcoholic liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E presents with elevated aminotransferase (AST and ALT) levels, usually \u0026lt; 300 U/L (and almost always \u0026lt; 500 U/L). The AST:ALT ratio is usually \u2265 2,\u003Cstrong\u003E so option c is correct with an AST:ALT ratio of 2:1.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to alcohol, \u003Cstrong\u003Enon-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD)\u003C/strong\u003E is another common cause, but NAFLD has AST and ALT \u0026lt; 100 U/L with AST:ALT \u0026lt;1. While this patient has hypercholesterolaemia, they are not obese and have no other features of metabolic syndrome, making this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther causes of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute hepatitis\u003C/strong\u003E, like acute viral hepatitis (e.g. from Hep A), toxic hepatitis (e.g. from paracetamol overdose), and ischaemic hepatitis present with aminotransferase levels \u0026gt; 1,000 U/L (but the AST:ALT is usually \u0026lt; 1). This patient has no risk factors for acute viral hepatitis (e.g. no exposures such as oysters) or toxic hepatitis (no paracetamol or complementary medicine usage) or ischaemic hepatitis (no vascular risk factors no periods of hypotension).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alcoholic hepatitis presents with elevated ALT and AST, usually less than 300 U/L, with an AST:ALT ratio \u2265 2.","Chronic alcohol consumption can lead to macrocytic anaemia and thrombocytopenia due to bone marrow suppression and liver dysfunction."],"references":["Botros M, Sikaris KA. The de ritis ratio: the test of time. Clin Biochem Rev. 2013 Nov;34(3):117-30. PMID: 24353357; PMCID: PMC3866949. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24353357/","Torruellas C, French SW, Medici V. Diagnosis of alcoholic liver disease. World J Gastroenterol. 2014 Sep 7;20(33):11684-99. doi: 10.3748/wjg.v20.i33.11684. PMID: 25206273; PMCID: PMC4155359. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546632/","Patel R, Mueller M. Alcohol-Associated Liver Disease. [Updated 2023 Jul 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK546632/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89792"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11964"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89792"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-27T22:50:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-27T22:52:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4556"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107328"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji